  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Gill's Exposition of the Entire Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Then Toi sent Joram his son unto King David,.... Who is called Hadoram in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 18:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; though the Syriac and Arabic versions read Joram there: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "to salute him: to inquire of his welfare after his fatigue in the battles he had had with the Moabites and Syrians, and to wish him all happiness and prosperity for the future: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and to bless him; to congratulate him on his victory, and to wish him success in all after wars he might be engaged in; and particularly to give him thanks for delivering him from so great an enemy as Hadadezer had been to him, as also to bring a present to him, which is sometimes called a blessing; see Genesis 33:11, ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "and to bless him; to congratulate him on his victory, and to wish him success in all after wars he might be engaged in; and particularly to give him thanks for delivering him from so great an enemy as Hadadezer had been to him, as also to bring a present to him, which is sometimes called a blessing; see ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Genesis 33:11",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", ",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "because he had fought against Hadadezer, and smitten him; that is, David had, which had endeared him to Toi: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "for Hadadezer had wars with Toi; was an enemy of his, sought to take his kingdom from him, and had had many battles with him: and though he could not conquer him, he sadly harassed him, being too mighty for him: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and Joram brought with him vessels of silver, and vessels of gold,  ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and vessels of brass; as a present to David, in gratitude for his deliverance from his enemy by him, and as a token of his homage and subjection to him; at least as a sign that he put himself under his protection, and desired to be his friend and ally. The word \"Joram\", though not in the Hebrew text, is rightly supplied; for none else can be supposed to bring the present. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "and vessels of brass; as a present to David, in gratitude for his deliverance from his enemy by him, and as a token of his homage and subjection to him; at least as a sign that he put himself under his protection, and desired to be his friend and ally. The word \"Joram\", though not in the Hebrew text, is rightly supplied; for none else can be supposed to bring the present. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
